##The Lamp Project: they deliver goods, warmth and love

WMSYGSDR

Functional introduction, each line has a serious person, even ordinary people have extraordinary stories. Huazhong University of Science and Technology Press Official non-fiction story platform, the story of the people will meet here.

On January 25, the first day of the Lunar New Year, more than 200 volunteers from all walks of life set up the "lamp project" to solve the shortage of materials in the capital city of Hubei Province. Taking advantage of their respective expertise, they registered 633 items of material requirements in Hubei's city-level hospitals in a two-day period, and passed the baton through various links such as fund-raising, procurement, storage and transportation.

They work enthusiastically for no pay and are often depressed by physical overload and misperceptions.

"I worked hard when I started my own business, but I've never been so busy, " said Bai Bai, a volunteer buyer. With cysts in her body, she had recently suffered palpitations, chest tightness, headaches, and Tinnitus, and was blamed for not getting supplies in time. But she felt unable to give up, "If we do not do these things, then how to do so many hospitals, we can not watch AH! "

Calls for help from cities around Wuhan

Young screenwriter Christian Diotzen has become an unlikely co-founder of the lamp project. Her cousin runs a wholesale company of textile and clothing raw materials and accessories in Guangzhou. On the morning of January 23, her cousin and three of them set off from Guangzhou, driving for more than 30 hours, the 370,000 masks and a supply of disinfectant were delivered to the CDC in Jingzhou, where they are based.

On the afternoon of the 24th, "Just asked my brother to leave 50 masks for me, no mask, normal mask, no N95, no mail, free mask, " diotzen posted on a friend circle, social media platform big V "rabbit torn chicken master" saw the sentence.

He posted the story of Diozen and his cousin online. In just one hour, hundreds of people added masks to diocen's wechat request, including medical workers and ordinary people. After chatting with these people, diocen was surprised to find that the degree of material shortage in the cities around Wuhan was also Psycho. This was the first time she actually heard "a cry for help from the front line. "

Diotzen first set up a "wechat group of mutual help in the surrounding cities of Wuhan" , pulling in all the hospitals with material needs. Through communication and investigation, she quickly put together a "list of medical materials for help in the surrounding cities of Wuhan" , "You should know that the number of suspected infections in the small cities around Wuhan is larger than the total number of provinces, and we hope that people pay more attention to us! "

After graduating from college in 2018, Ms. Diotzen jumped from one job to another more than 10 times in a year. "I couldn't stay, " she said. At that point, she began reaching out to her former employers, one by one, with a "list of things to do. " Add them to the support group. With the help of big V, "Rabbit Tearing Chicken Big Lord" , in a day or two, the number of volunteers in the group has expanded to more than 200 people.

Volunteers come in all shapes and sizes, from company executives to college teachers to overseas Chinese, from farmers to barbecue owners, from insurance salesmen to manicurist hostesses to wechat business agents.

Finding it crowded but lacking a central organizer, he contacted Internet product manager horsepower, who is also well connected and runs a group of 77 product managers. Ji Feng Net founder Tan Yi also joined in, after the group began to take charge of the overall leadership coordination.

On January 25th, on the first day of the Lunar New Year, the group was given a name: "lamp-burning project" -- meaning to help solve the shortage of medical facilities in non-provincial cities in Hubei Province and prevent "darkness under the lamp" .

From January 25 to 27, they registered a total of 633 materials demand information of municipal hospitals in Hubei Province. In order to improve the efficiency of material circulation, they quickly divided the volunteers in the group into several groups, such as the "purchasing group" , the "fundraising group" , and the "Logistics Group" . They also set up "temporary warehouses" in various cities in Hubei. After the materials arrived, the districts rely on teams of volunteers recruited to transport supplies to the hospitals.

Questionable procurement of supplies

Diotzen was mainly in charge of sourcing. Domestic manufacturers of medical supplies are already in short supply, and many have been taken over by the government, she set her sights on overseas. Never engaged in overseas trade, she stepped on many pits at first, tried her best to buy a batch of goods back, but could not be donated to the medical staff because it did not meet the requirements.

After being introduced by a friend, she found a mask manufacturer in Australia. "Not only did the boss not raise the price, but he donated 10,000 yuan out of his own pocket. " However, due to his lack of English expertise, she thought the masks did not have valves. After ordering, she read the instructions carefully and found that they did not have the words "liquid spray" in them, meaning they could not be provided to front-line health care workers. A Hong Kong company wanted to make a pledge and decided to donate the masks to welfare homes for the elderly and sanitation workers. "being a civilian is a good result, but right now I'm mainly trying to address the immediate needs of front-line health care workers. "

To avoid making the same mistake again, she took her translator and looked for the technical term "anti-splash" in the instruction manuals of various languages. When she couldn't handle it, she sent out a friend's circle for help, she then set up a small group of volunteer translators and sent messages to them for help.

"My friend joked to me that after the outbreak was over, you could go and do business overseas, " she said. "after the outbreak, you can go and do business overseas. "

Because of jet lag, diozen often replies to messages in the middle of the night, especially in the first few days, and can only sleep four hours a day. High-intensity use of her eyes to get acute conjunctivitis, eyes red and swollen to make her mother startled. Her mother loved her, but she couldn't bear to give up, and she felt like she was going to collapse, hiding in the bathroom and crying. As the shopping got easier, she promised her family that they would be in bed by 1:00 at night.

Like Diotzen, Baibai experienced the same moment of collapse. "I worked hard enough when I started my own business, but I've never been so busy. "

Bai Bai's mother, a national nutritionist and folk dietician, resigned in early 2017 to start a chili sauce business with her and later opened a rice noodle shop. Due to overwork, Baibai was found to have a cyst in her body at the end of 2019 and was forced to rest and recuperate.

On the second day of the Lunar New Year, Tan Yi found her when she had just returned to Beijing from her hometown in Nanchang, Jiangxi Province. When she entered the group, she was frightened by the information that the county hospitals in the group were in short supply. "In Qichun County, under Huanggang, there is a hospital director who says the hospital staff are now running around naked, without masks or protective clothing. I could feel him crying between the lines, " Bai said, adding that he even saw a hospital Adult diaper: "They couldn't take off their protective suits to go to the bathroom. They went in in their diapers, and they didn't eat or drink for eight hours, which made my heart ache. "

For more than a week after I took over the procurement, I felt as if I was going crazy every day from nine in the morning to two in the evening, trying to communicate on my cell phone except for dinner. "At the end of the day, I often feel my eyes are going to fall out. Every time I wear contact lenses, I feel very painful. I can't put them on at all. Every night after 11 o'clock, I start to have heart palpitations, chest tightness, headache, tinnitus... it's not easy to do charity work, " Bai said.

To save time, she didn't even wash her hair or shower. After a few days, N95, KF94, KN95, FFP3, FFP2... She knows the models and prices by heart. "disposable medical masks cost $2 each, N95 MASKS $10 to $20, ISOLATION SUITS $10 to $20, goggles $17 to $27, which are low prices to buy. "

"It was very difficult to find the source of goods. We finally found the source of goods that met the standard. We had already paid for the goods to be shipped. Suddenly we were informed that the goods had been requisitioned by the government. Either the logistics had stopped taking orders... " various temporary conditions tested the White House, what's more, the pledging companies will also come asking for donations.

Students at one school raised money on their own to buy goggles and donate them to hospitals in Xiaogan. As a result, three or four days passed, no. Logistics delayed feedback, some students put forward questions. The person in charge of raising capital again and again urges white, white then urges the factory, in fact the factory also already overloads the movement. She said that she felt aggrieved by the words she spent on it every day: "Why would we be suspected of doing a good deed when we don't ask for any money or anything in return? "

In fact, at the beginning of doing this thing, a friend had warned Bai Bai, this kind of folk behavior risk is very big, in case where did not do in place, it is easy to call into question or even report. For this reason they also specifically consulted a lawyer, but the current epidemic, White feel "if not to do these things, so many hospitals how to do, we can not look! "

A heavily fortified road of transportation

In the whole civil relief chain of medical and nursing materials, besides "purchase materials" , "logistics transportation" has become more and more difficult along with "Wuhan Fengcheng" and "Hubei Fengsheng" . Since January 25, SF express and other logistics companies have issued a notice: all other goods shipped to Hubei Province Express delivery only to Wuhan, non-wuhan areas temporarily unable to distribute.

After the outbreak, she bought 30,000 pairs of Protective Shoe covers to donate to health care. She placed an order at 12 pm and returned it early the next morning because "logistics couldn't deliver" . After consulting with the factory, Meng Li decided to send the goods to Wuhan First, and then send someone to Wuhan to pull the goods.

Jingzhou is more than 220 kilometers away from Wuhan, but on the day of preparing to go to Wuhan, Jingzhou issued a "city closure order" . All motor vehicles were forbidden to pass. They had to run to the epidemic prevention headquarters again to apply for passes, it took a lot of work to get the supplies back.

On February 12,13 tons of alcohol from the Coordinating Organization of Bangladesh and Lebanon were transported from Shandong to Hubei.

In order to improve the speed of logistics operation, Meng Li quickly took out 10,000 square meters of the market area as a temporary warehouse, for various civilian relief supplies to provide transit volunteer services, and arrange security, cleaning staff on duty. She has been added to a number of civilian relief groups, as long as there are logistics storage needs, she tried to coordinate arrangements.

Immediately afterwards, the group that Meng Li belongs to also successively took out commercial real estate in Wuhan, Tianmen and other cities to use as transit warehouses for medical and nursing materials, "It's much more efficient. For example, a few days ago there was a shipment of 11,000 masks for hospitals in Jingzhou, and they could be sent directly to our temporary warehouse. Materials from other regions can also be transferred through us, and we take them to the highway and hand them over."

Located in the southwest of Hubei Province, nearly 800 kilometers from Wuhan, Ensch's Tujia and Miao Autonomous Prefecture is almost entirely mountainous, and its remote location and harsh terrain make it more difficult to transport medical supplies than other cities in the province. As of February 9, nearly 200 new cases of coronavirus pneumonia had been confirmed in Ensch.

Liu Shaoshan joined the "burning lamp project" voluntary organization, he combed out the needs of more than 100 local Ensch hospitals information, soon he became Ensch regional coordination team leader, almost every day he worked from eight o'clock in the morning to one or two o'clock in the evening, calling hundreds of times a day.

On February 1, he received word that 9,000 masks had been sent from Qianjiang to a temporary warehouse in Jingzhou, requiring him to arrange for a driver to travel from Ensch to Jingzhou to bring supplies back to Ensch hospitals. "Who wants to go? " He asked a local group of "volunteer motorcades" in Ensch. More than a dozen people soon responded, and eventually Liu, on the recommendation of the group members, chose to let Wang Zhuangmo go.

When he received the assignment, Wang was at his home in Longfeng, a town 16 kilometers from downtown Ensch. At about 5:00 p.m. that day, he drove to the Health Commission to apply for a pass. At that time, the road in the village had already been closed. He had to show his intention by presenting his information about the volunteers he had signed up for. After some verification, he was released, the same question came up again after arriving at the Ensch Health Commission: "Do you have an official stamp to prove that the mask you shipped was for donation rather than commercial use? "

In desperation, Wang Zhuangmo presented all his information, including his ID card, license plate number, home address, company business license, and volunteer registration form, and repeatedly said that he was "doing his part for the country. " Finally got a pass from Ensch to Jingzhou.

At 8:30 a.m. on the 2nd, it began to rain lightly in Ensch. Before leaving, Wang went to Ensch central hospital to get a protective suit and a mask for use when he arrived in Jingzhou. "Jingzhou is one of the most affected areas, and to be honest, I was scared, so I had to be careful. "

Just like yesterday, before he left the city, Wang Zhuangmo had been stopped by the police twice.

The first time, he was stopped by two female traffic police officers, who took his temperature and checked his pass. The Trunk Lid of the police car was open, and a laptop was placed under an umbrella to register the personnel information of the passing vehicles, while the police stand in the rain, naked on duty.

The second time, after crossing an intersection, he was stopped by the police. The policeman was wearing only an ordinary mask. The rain had completely soaked the mask, and the wind blew the mask all over his mouth, making it difficult to speak. It is said that Wang Zhuangmo is going to haul the masks, the policeman is very hope he can give several pairs of masks. Seeing him standing in the rain, Wang almost felt like crying, so he quickly sent a message in the "volunteer motorcade" group. An hour later, another motorist surnamed Zhang sent the policeman a mask.

Ensch to Jingzhou about 300 kilometers, more than four hours drive Wang Zhuangmo did not dare delay a moment. There were only short stops in two service areas, where half a dozen cars were parked thinly, and only instant noodles were served. Wang Zhuangmo always pay attention to the tap of the switch, the toilet door handle did not dare to touch directly.

Shortly after 12:00 noon, Wang was about to arrive in Jingzhou when he received a call from Liu Shaoshan -- Foshan -- because of traffic control, the goods could not reach Jingzhou and had to be towed from Qianjiang. This means not only running more than 100 kilometers to get supplies, but also spending a lot of time and energy to undergo a traffic check at a road junction.

At the Jingzhou Highway Junction alone, Wang lost more than an hour. More than 20 cars are waiting in a queue to be disinfected. The driver is crowded in a shed to register his information. Wang Zhuangmo is afraid of cross infection. He dare not go down until he has put on a protective suit and a mask.

It was a little after two in the afternoon when Wang finally drove to Qianjiang. He followed the directions and headed toward the city, only to find that nearly all the entrances to the city were blocked by steel pipes, making it impossible for vehicles to pass. He quickly called a local friend in Qianjiang for help, and with that friend, he found the only intersection that allowed him to enter downtown Qianjiang. He once again encountered a cross-examination, in a number of telephone calls, one by one to check the information, and finally released.

As soon as the supplies are loaded, Wang Zhuang Mo rushes back. It was evening in Ensch, with heavy fog in the city, poor visibility and the winding of the mountain roads, and Wang was more careful not to drive too fast, until just after 9 p.m. , when the supplies were finally towed back. All the way down, the total cost of the gas tolls more than 1000 yuan, all out of Wang Zhuangmo's own pocket, Liu Shaoshan originally wanted to use the funds raised to reimbursement, but Wang Zhuangmo refused.

The supplies were put in a van downstairs in EIKO's neighborhood. EIKO has been acting as a wechat agent for women's personal care products since 2014. After six years, she has established her own stable team and marketing channel. In 2018, she also joined the Association for the care and Protection of left-behind children in Ensch, peer-to-peer support for poor local children.

After the outbreak, she was quickly drawn into a variety of civilian relief groups. Boldly and carefully she volunteered to take out the family van as a temporary transit warehouse. When the 9,000 masks arrived, Eiko arranged them according to how many hospitals gave out, and the next morning, medical staff from hospitals in Lichuan, Padang, Laifeng, and other counties and townships came one after another to collect supplies. "They are really short of supplies. Many hospitals drive more than two hours to get 20 masks. "

Hospital receipt for EIKO's supplies.

Because of daily exposure to a large number of health care workers, Eiko was armed with protective clothing, goggles, and masks. In order not to waste the scarce medical supplies, Eiko had to stay downstairs all the time after putting them on, in case neighbors stopped by to ask, she would sit behind the delivery cabinet with a stool, and after a while, she would shiver with cold and go upstairs at night too tired to say a word.

Two days ago, the son suddenly burned to 37.2 degrees Celsius, Eiko sister heart tight, "if the family, community people infected, then I am a sinner! " said she could not help sobbing.

Finding "meaning" in life through aid

Not all of the volunteers were able to stick it out. The intensity of the work and the demand for competence and professionalism have caused many people to quit in the middle.

The reason why the white dragged exhausted body insist on doing, is that by the "positive feedback. ". These days, the group is no longer the same as the previous day in the hospital every day to send help screen, this improvement makes her feel that what she did can really help them. "No matter how tired I am, I want to hold on a little longer. "

The "positive feedback" received in vain.

Liu Shaoshan is that found the "sense of meaning. ". He opened a car trim store in 2014, and after five or six years in which his income was not proportional to his investment, and depression, he decided to close the store and work as a salesman for an insurance company. He did not expect, in the career has not had the "sense of accomplishment" , during this period of experience. "When you can really help someone, you think it's a great thing to do. "

The epidemic continues. People are looking forward to spring. Before long, people who have come together out of love will return to their lives and work.

Diotzen has recently started telecommuting, working on short video projects as she plans her next pro bono action. She felt that there would always be a day when the disaster would pass, but that the trauma of those who had lost loved ones to the epidemic would always be there.

Among the volunteers she knew was Wan Qing, a Sichuan businessman whose uncle had died of new coronavirus pneumonia, and whose parents and relatives had been quarantined. In his grief, Wanqing mobilized all his resources, organized logistics convoys, donated 1m GB surgical masks to his hometown of Xiaogan, and is now sourcing and delivering supplies to other cities. "You say, for someone like brother Wan, he doesn't need money at all, but how do you deal with the loss of a loved one? " She wanted to find someone to do a long-term warmth program to focus on and help the traumatized.

Bai Bai is thinking of her own hot sauce business, she would like to donate a batch of hot sauce after the festival, "Hubei people also like to eat spicy. ". She had just rented two new storefronts years ago and had already paid the rent. She had planned to start decorating after the holidays, but now she had to wait.

"The money on the books will last two or three months at the most, " she said. But with the experience, she felt that there was always a way out. "Good people deserve good things, right? "

(at the request of the interviewees, sister Diotzen, Bai Bai, Meng Li and Eiko were given pseudonyms. Thanks also to Zang Xinyu and Luo, volunteers of the lamp project, for their interview materials.)
